understanding that people, in addition to

00:03:58.999 --> 00:04:04.559
wanting to go out to be entertained by food,
that what they really wanna do is understand

00:04:04.559 --> 00:04:08.680
their food, they wanna love their food and
they wanna know about their food.

00:04:08.680 --> 00:04:15.609
Thirty years ago, you became a cook, not a
chef, right after you got out of the military

00:04:15.609 --> 00:04:18.480
and some time before you went to jail.

00:04:18.480 --> 00:04:19.480
[laughter]

00:04:19.480 --> 00:04:23.770
And that's because cooking at that time was
the lowest common denominator job. Anybody

00:04:23.770 --> 00:04:27.800
could peel a potato, anybody could start in
a kitchen, and effectively work in a diner

00:04:27.800 --> 00:04:37.340
in any town or in the military-- or in prison--cooking
food. Our fascination with food came as a

00:04:37.340 --> 00:04:41.979
result of our fascination with our health,
our understanding of our health, our fascination

00:04:41.979 --> 00:04:46.699
with the things that give us pleasure. And
I must say, I'm quite pleased to say that

00:04:46.699 --> 00:04:51.199
whereas 30 years ago you might go out to get
a bite and then go to the game or go to the

00:04:51.199 --> 00:04:56.509
opera and then get a bite, or go to a concert
or a museum and get something to eat on the

00:04:56.509 --> 00:05:00.910
way, at this point now amongst many of the
people in this room, the bite is actually

00:05:00.910 --> 00:05:06.689
the central part of our evening or our afternoon.
And it's our obsession and our pride and our

00:05:06.689 --> 00:05:12.009
understanding, as well as our internationalization
in our super Suave' Bolla way that we travel

00:05:12.009 --> 00:05:16.270
around the world and look for things that
make us happy, that food has come to the center

00:05:16.270 --> 00:05:20.520
of the plate, as it were. Subsequent to that,
of course, cooks became a little bit more

00:05:20.520 --> 00:05:28.370
successful. And it's in no short, it's not
to short it, but I think that although cooks

00:05:28.370 --> 00:05:32.780
have enjoyed a certain little bit of fame,
eventually the next rock stars aren't gonna

00:05:32.780 --> 00:05:36.030
be cooks. It's gonna be farmer's [looks to
the left and sighs] and fishermen because

00:05:36.030 --> 00:05:40.000
eventually you'll realize that no matter how
much technique there is and how many bams

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:44.470
there is or how many squirt bottles there
is, or all of those other things, effectively

00:05:44.470 --> 00:05:48.580
what really is the biggest decision is you're
going to make are going to be on what you

00:05:48.580 --> 00:05:52.759
buy and how you source it and where you get
it. So, there's also shopping parts in this

00:05:52.759 --> 00:05:57.320
app, but I think the real understanding is
to make something delicious, you really have

00:05:57.320 --> 00:06:02.629
to buy something that has a point of view.
And it's that kind of slow-food mentality,

00:06:02.629 --> 00:06:08.130
that kind of searching for biodiversity that
is what I really try to represent at this

00:06:08.130 --> 00:06:10.740
point. I don't know if any of you have heard
about this little grocery store I opened up

00:06:10.740 --> 00:06:17.520
called Eataly on 23rd Street. But if you walk
in there there's a, there's a huge component

00:06:17.520 --> 00:06:24.370
of it is slogans. It's allowing people to
understand that it's one little bite of information

00:06:24.370 --> 00:06:29.280
that will allow you to really get your hands
on what a great tangerine is, or why you eat

00:06:29.280 --> 00:06:33.069
this kind of spaghetti or what kind of oil
this is. And it's not really about Italian

00:06:33.069 --> 00:06:37.740
food. It's about the micro-regional components
of Italian food and American ingredients as

00:06:37.740 --> 00:06:43.169
well, cooked into that world that make it
so satisfying to do and so delicious and also

00:06:43.169 --> 00:06:48.520
nutritious for you. So, this app has all of
that rolled into it and what it really is

00:06:48.520 --> 00:06:53.530
about is empowering you to understand that
you can cook just like I can, almost as good

00:06:53.530 --> 00:06:57.759
as some of the great grandmothers from Italy.
And that's the objective behind this is to

00:06:57.759 --> 00:07:02.419
remove a little bit more of the veil, to look
a little bit behind the curtain, but effectively

00:07:02.419 --> 00:07:06.600
