00:17:17.890 --> 00:17:22.600
that has increased exponentially over the
last ten years. Why? What do you think has

00:17:22.600 --> 00:17:25.949
driven that change in how we think about food?

00:17:25.949 --> 00:17:30.480
&gt;&gt;Mario Batali: Well, I think food became
a significant part of people understanding

00:17:30.480 --> 00:17:35.600
that not only should they exercise, but they
should eat well. I think that information

00:17:35.600 --> 00:17:41.310
became much more diffuse with the rise of
the Food Network and then subsequently with

00:17:41.310 --> 00:17:47.150
the rise of social media and technology. I
think that it's now very much part of the

00:17:47.150 --> 00:17:52.240
game to share information very quickly as
it comes out, as you hear about something.

00:17:52.240 --> 00:17:55.790
And the way that we do it now, it used to
be that we wrote letters and then we used

00:17:55.790 --> 00:18:02.090
the phone and then we used the handheld phone
and now we can virtually send any piece of

00:18:02.090 --> 00:18:07.690
media, any long short document, any piece
of video from cell phone to cell phone, from

00:18:07.690 --> 00:18:13.680
handheld to handheld, in seconds. So, the
information gets out. It's much more widely

00:18:13.680 --> 00:18:17.511
read. It's much more widely appreciated and
the sophistication of the people that are

00:18:17.511 --> 00:18:22.210
reading what used to be a Betty Crocker recipe
are now much more fascinated in the idea of

00:18:22.210 --> 00:18:27.020
not only regional Italian cooking, but they
understand the difference between the cooking

00:18:27.020 --> 00:18:31.880
of Puglia and the cooking of a town in Puglia
called Bari. And then when you wanna talk

00:18:31.880 --> 00:18:36.150
about what really makes Bari interesting,
is the kind of fish that they use there or

00:18:36.150 --> 00:18:40.030
the kind of sweet peppers they use in their
fish stew and suddenly there's a whole level

00:18:40.030 --> 00:18:46.450
of sophistication that travel around and as
we will all realize very quickly in the next

00:18:46.450 --> 00:18:51.980
ten years, when all content will become free,
then we're gonna really see how that kind

00:18:51.980 --> 00:18:57.590
of information goes out. And it's gonna be
much more tied to how you create the relationships

00:18:57.590 --> 00:19:02.860
between the content provider and the content
user that's going to make the really big difference.

00:19:02.860 --> 00:19:06.360
And the advertisers and the book companies
and, sadly, the record companies have missed

00:19:06.360 --> 00:19:10.590
the entire boat, are all starting to really
pay attention to how this information's getting

00:19:10.590 --> 00:19:15.270
out. And that's, that's the real next ten
year generation ideology. It's how we're going

00:19:15.270 --> 00:19:19.950
to monetize something, but how also we're
gonna take credit for our own ideas in a world

00:19:19.950 --> 00:19:26.310
where it's shared so quickly that it's everyone's
idea at the same time. Which is good, this

00:19:26.310 --> 00:19:28.780
is good. Don't get me wrong. It's not a, not
a bad thing.

